<p><span style="font-family: tahoma, sans-serif;">In C and C++, preprocessor directives are essentially special lines of code in the program, usually denoted by having different syntax and starting with a <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">#</span>. For instance,</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: monospace, sans-serif;">#include &lt;iostream&gt;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: tahoma, sans-serif;">is a preprocessor directive. When you go to compile your program (whether using the VS compiler, GNU C Compiler, CLANG, Intel C++ Compiler, etc), the preprocessor program changes the source code based on the preprocessor directives. In the aforementioned<span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;"> #include &lt;iostream&gt;</span>, as far as I know the preprocessor actually replaces the statement with all of the <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">iostream</span> header. In my case, <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">iostream</span> is located at&nbsp;<span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">/usr/include/c++/6.1.1/iostream</span>, but this of course can change based on your platform (GNU/Linux, OSX, Windows, BSD, etc).&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: tahoma, sans-serif;">As well, the preprocessor can include or exclude code at compile time. For example, I do my coding on a Linux machine, but it needs to be able to compile and execute natively on Windows. So if I want the "<span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">Press any key to continue...</span>" (or similar) line to appear no matter if the program's being executed on my laptop or one of PCC's Windows boxes, I can use the code</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">#ifdef __unix__<br /> cout &lt;&lt; "Press any key&nbsp;to continue..." &lt;&lt; flush;<br />system("read -n1");</span><span style="font-family: tahoma, sans-serif;"><br /><span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">#elif defined(_WIN32) || defined(WIN32)</span><br /><span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;"> system("pause");</span><br /><span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">#endif</span><br /></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: tahoma, sans-serif;">So in this case, the <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">#ifdef</span> and <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">#elif</span> statements tell the preprocessor that if the code is being compiled on Linux or a POSIX UNIX-based system, the entire block of code from the <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">#ifdef</span> to the <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">#endif</span> should be thrown out and replaced with the <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">cout</span> and <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">system("read -n1")</span> statements. Similarly, if it's being compiled on Windows, the code should be replaced with the <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">system("pause")</span> statement.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: tahoma, sans-serif;">As well, the preprocessor removes comments and replaces text such as "<span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">and</span>," "<span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">or</span>," and "<span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">not</span>" with their symbol equivalents, <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">&amp;&amp;</span>, <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">||</span>, and <span style="font-family: 'monospace', sans-serif;">!</span>, respectively.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: tahoma, sans-serif;">VS won't have any buttons or anything for the preprocessor as any and all directives are defined in your program. Well, there might be a button for an easy #include &lt;whatever&gt;, but I haven't had the chance to poke around the interface much.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: tahoma, sans-serif;"></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: tahoma, sans-serif;">Hope this answers any questions!</span></p>
